1. Objective
Build a purpose-built reconciliation tool that validates the accuracy and completeness of data backfilled from Infra Spanner to Cloud Spanner as part of the Budget Manager migration from Google BoQ to Google Cloud. The tool will perform table-level and row-level comparisons across all 90 tables, surface discrepancies in a structured report, and provide the team with confidence that the migrated data is production-ready before cutover.
2. Background
2.1 Migration Context
Budget Manager is migrating from Google BoQ (running on Infra Spanner) to Google Cloud (running on Cloud Spanner). The first phase of this migration involves backfilling historical data from the Infra Spanner instance into the new Cloud Spanner instance. This backfill is a prerequisite to running both systems in parallel and ultimately cutting over to Cloud.
2.2 Why Reconciliation Is Needed
Data integrity is critical for FP&A workflows. Budget Manager supports financial planning, forecasting, and reporting processes where even small discrepancies—missing rows, truncated values, mismatched timestamps—can cascade into material errors. A reconciliation step between the source (Infra Spanner) and target (Cloud Spanner) is essential to certify the backfill before enabling downstream consumption.
2.3 Scale of the Problem
Approximately 90 tables must be compared across the two Spanner instances.
Tables vary significantly in schema complexity, row count, and data types.
Infra Spanner and Cloud Spanner use different query engines, which limits the feasibility of a one-size-fits-all comparison approach.
Some tables contain billions of rows, requiring efficient sampling or partitioned comparison strategies.
3. Proposal
3.1 Overview
We propose building a custom reconciliation tool that connects to both the Infra Spanner and Cloud Spanner instances, reads data from each, and performs configurable comparisons. The tool will output a discrepancy report highlighting mismatches at the table, row, and column level.
3.2 Core Capabilities
Schema validation: Compare table schemas (column names, types, constraints) between Infra and Cloud.
Row-count reconciliation: Verify that each table in Cloud contains the expected number of rows relative to Infra.
Content-level comparison: For each table, perform row-by-row or hash-based comparison of data values, flagging mismatches.
Configurable table list: Allow teams to specify which tables to reconcile, with support for inclusion/exclusion filters.
Discrepancy reporting: Generate structured output (CSV/dashboard) with table name, column, primary key, expected vs. actual values, and severity classification.
Tolerance and rule configuration: Support configurable tolerances for numeric fields and timestamp drift to reduce false positives.
3.3 Architecture
The tool will be built as a standalone service that authenticates to both Spanner instances using service accounts. It will operate in three phases:
Phase 1 – Schema Diff: Pull DDL from both instances and compare programmatically.
Phase 2 – Row Count & Checksum: Run aggregate queries (COUNT, FARM_FINGERPRINT) on each table and compare results.
Phase 3 – Deep Diff: For tables with count or checksum mismatches, perform partitioned row-level comparison using primary key ranges.
3.4 Key Design Decisions
Engine abstraction layer: Because Infra Spanner and Cloud Spanner expose different client libraries and SQL dialects, the tool will include an abstraction layer that normalizes query construction and result parsing across both engines.
Parallel execution: Comparisons will run concurrently across tables to stay within acceptable time windows for large datasets.
Incremental mode: Support delta reconciliation for ongoing backfill operations, comparing only rows modified after a given timestamp.
3.5 Success Criteria
100% of 90 tables reconciled with zero unresolved critical discrepancies before cutover.
Schema parity confirmed for all migrated tables.
Reconciliation run completes within [TBD] hours for the full dataset.
Discrepancy report is reviewable by the migration team without requiring manual SQL queries.
4. Alternatives Considered
4.1 PLX (Preferred Alternative)
PLX is Google’s internal data analysis platform and was evaluated as the primary alternative for performing reconciliation.
Why PLX Was Not Selected
Different query engines: Infra Spanner and Cloud Spanner use fundamentally different engines. PLX pipelines cannot issue queries against both engines within a single, unified pipeline without significant workarounds.
90-table scale: Writing and maintaining individual PLX queries or pipelines for each of the 90 tables is operationally expensive and error-prone. A generalized PLX approach is not feasible because each table has unique schema characteristics.
Limited flexibility: PLX is optimized for batch analytics, not for row-level comparison with configurable tolerance rules, primary-key-based diffing, and structured discrepancy reporting.
Maintenance overhead: Any schema change in the source or target would require updating the corresponding PLX pipeline, creating a fragile dependency.
4.2 Manual Spot-Checks
An approach based on manually querying a sample of tables and visually inspecting results was considered but rejected. This does not scale to 90 tables, provides no audit trail, and risks missing edge-case discrepancies that only surface in full-dataset comparison.
